# test to see if the itemset lists are equal
def itemset_to_ordered_string(itemset):
    return ','.join(sorted(list(itemset)))

apriori_itemset_strings_all = model_apriori_all_com['itemsets'].apply(itemset_to_ordered_string)
apriori_itemset_strings_all = apriori_itemset_strings_all.sort_values().reset_index(drop=True)

fpgrowth_itemset_strings_all = model_fpgrowth_all_com['itemsets'].apply(itemset_to_ordered_string)
fpgrowth_itemset_strings_all = fpgrowth_itemset_strings_all.sort_values().reset_index(drop=True)


#Cheking if apriori results are the same as jpgrowth
fpgrowth_itemset_strings_all.equals(apriori_itemset_strings_all)
Out[10]:
True
Conclusion: The results of the values are equal, so the JP Growth was chosen over Apriori because it usually has a better performance.¶

#Plot the complementary products
Plot_rules_all = rules_all_com

Plot_rules_all['length_ant'] = rules_all_com['antecedents'].apply(lambda x: len(x))
Plot_rules_all['length_cons'] = rules_all_com['consequents'].apply(lambda x: len(x))


# Replace frozen sets with strings
Plot_rules_all['antecedents_'] = rules_all_com['antecedents'].apply(lambda a: ','.join(list(a)))
Plot_rules_all['consequents_'] = rules_all_com['consequents'].apply(lambda a: ','.join(list(a)))


# Transform the DataFrame of rules into a matrix using the lift metric
pivot_all = Plot_rules_all[Plot_rules_all['length_ant']==1].pivot(index = 'antecedents_', 
                    columns = 'consequents_', values= 'lift')


# Generate a heatmap with annotations on and the colorbar off
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,10)) 
sns.heatmap(pivot_all, annot = True, linewidths=.5, ax=ax, cmap="Blues").set_title("Complementary Products")

plt.savefig('heatmap_all_rules_all_dataset.png',bbox_inches='tight',dpi=250, transparent=True)

plt.show()

### Plot a basic network graph of the top 30 lift rules
# Create a copy of the rules and transform the frozensets to strings
rulesToPlot = rules_WW_com.copy(deep=True)
rulesToPlot['ant'] = [','.join(list(x)) for x in rulesToPlot['antecedents']]
rulesToPlot['cons'] = [','.join(list(x)) for x in rulesToPlot['consequents']]
# Remove duplicate if reversed rules
rulesToPlot['sortedRow'] = [sorted([a,b]) for a,b in zip(rulesToPlot.ant, rulesToPlot.cons)]
rulesToPlot['sortedRow'] = rulesToPlot['sortedRow'].astype(str)
rulesToPlot.drop_duplicates(subset=['sortedRow'], inplace=True)
# Plot
rulesToPlot=rulesToPlot[:30]
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20, 18)) 
G = nx.from_pandas_edgelist(rulesToPlot, 'ant', 'cons')  
# Each node is an itemset (either source or target) and the edges connect the itemsets if they consist of a high lift assocation rule
nx.draw(G, with_labels=True, node_size=200, node_color="red", pos=nx.spring_layout(G))
plt.axis('equal')
plt.show()
